{"cursor":"90337","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n {{Infobox scientist |name\n= Alhazen| |image = Ibn al-Haytham.png|upright |caption = 'Alhazen (Ibn al-\nHaytham)'| |birth_date = CE (354 AH) |\n|birth_place = Basra in present-day Iraq |death_date = \n(430 AH) | |death_place = Cairo, Egypt, Fatimid Caliphate |residence\n= Basra Cairo |citizenship = |nationality = |ethnicity = Persian |fields =\noptics, astronomy, mathematics |workplaces = |alma_mater = |notable_students =\n|influences = Aristotle, Euclid, Ptolemy |influenced = Averroes, Witelo, Roger\nBacon |known_for = [[Book of Optics]], Doubts Concerning Ptolemy, scientific\nmethod, experimental science, visual perception |footnotes = |Religion =\ntheist, school_tradition = Sunni Islam }}\n\n'{{transl|ar|ALA|AbÅ« Ê¿AlÄ« al-á¸¤asan ibn al-á¸¤asan ibn al-Haytham}}' (Persian : Ø§Ø¨Ù\nÙÙØ«Ù, Arabic: Ø£Ø¨Ù Ø¹ÙÙØ Ø§ÙØ­Ø³Ù Ø¨Ù Ø§ÙØ­Ø³Ù Ø¨Ù Ø§ÙÙÙØ«Ù, Latinized: 'Alhacen' or\n(deprecated) Lindberg, 1996. 'Alhazen') (965 in Basra â c. 1040 in\nCairo) was a Muslim http://www.amualumni.8m.com/Scientist3.htm http://www.islamic-\nstudy.org/optics.htm scientist, polymath, mathematician, astronomer and\nphilosopher, described in various sources as either Persian or Arab. \n  Understanding History by John Child, Paul Shuter, David Taylor - Page\n70. Science and Human Destiny by Norman F. Dessel,\nRichard B. Nehrich, Glenn I. Voran - Page 164. The Journal of Science, and\nAnnals of Astronomy, Biology, Geology by James Samuelson, William Crookes - Page\n497.    [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/738111/Ibn-al-\nHaytham]   [http://www.ibnalhaytham.net/custom.em?pid=571860 Review\nof Ibn al-Haytham: First Scientist], Kirkus Reviews, December 1, 2006: : :\n He made significant contributions to the principles of optics, as well as\nto astronomy, mathematics, visual perception, and to the scientific method. He\nalso wrote insightful commentaries on works by Aristotle, Ptolemy, and the Greek\nmathematician Euclid. \"[http://books.google.com/books?id=kZcCtT1ZeaEC&pg=PA-\n142&dq&hl=en#v=onepage&q=&f=false The rainbow bridge: rainbows in art, myth, and\nscience]\". Raymond L. Lee, Alistair B. Fraser (2001). Penn State Press. p.142.\nISBN 0-271-01977-8\n\nHe is frequently referred to as 'Ibn al-Haytham', and sometimes as 'al-Basri'\n(Arabic: Ø§ÙØ¨ØµØ±Ù), after his birthplace in the city of Basra.\nHe was also nicknamed Ptolemaeus Secundus (\"Ptolemy the Second\") or simply \"The Physicist\" in medieval Europe.\n\nBorn circa 965, in Basra, present-day Iraq, he lived mainly in Cairo, Egypt,\ndying there at age 74. According to one version of his\nbiography, overconfident about practical application of his mathematical\nknowledge, he assumed that he could regulate the floods of the Nile. After being ordered by Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, the sixth ruler\nof the Fatimid caliphate, to carry out this operation, he quickly perceived the\nimpossibility of what he was attempting to do, and retired from engineering.\nFearing for his life, he feigned madness and was placed under house arrest, during and after which he\ndevoted himself to his scientific work until his death.\nHe is known as the \"Father of modern optics and Scientific\nmethodology\" Abhandlung Ã¼ber das Licht\", J. Baarmann (ed. 1882) Zeitschrift\nder Deutschen MorgenlÃ¤ndischen Gesellschaft Vol 36 http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7810846.stm and could be\nregarded as the first theoretical physicist.\n","linknr":1873,"url":"Alhazen","recorded":1362477601,"links":96,"instances":["geometry","journal","mathematics","anatomy","physics","journal","book_publisher","medieval_writer","physics","journal","vision","literature","mathematics","crater","optics","city"],"pdf":["http://www.optics.arizona.edu/SSD/art-optics/papers/IEEECairo.pdf","http://www.optics.arizona.edu/SSD/art-optics/papers/IEEECairo.pdf","http://www.perceptionweb.com/perception/editorials/p5940.pdf","http://www.perceptionweb.com/perce